---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Resources"
  description="Books that shaped how I think, learning platforms worth your time, tools that didn't survive, and homelab projects that teach you more than any course."
>
  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-6">
        Resources: Books, Learning, and Lessons
      </h1>

      <p class="text-xl italic text-[var(--text-muted)] mb-8">
        The books that made me better at what I do, the learning platforms worth your time, and the tools that didn't
        survive contact with reality. No affiliate links, no vendor pitches.
      </p>

      <!-- Jump to -->
      <nav style="margin-block: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted);">
        Jump to:
        <a href="#books">Books</a> &middot;
        <a href="#graveyard">Tool Graveyard</a> &middot;
        <a href="#homelab">Homelab Projects</a> &middot;
        <a href="#learning">Learning Platforms</a> &middot;
        <a href="#security-news">Security News</a>
      </nav>

      <!-- Cross-link to /uses -->
      <div
        class="bg-[var(--surface)] border-l-4 border-[var(--text-muted)] p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg"
      >
        <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
          <strong>Looking for tools and software?</strong> My full setup &mdash; hardware, software, containers, and
          dev tools &mdash; lives on the <a href="/uses" class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium">/uses</a> page.
          This page focuses on books, learning paths, and the lessons behind the tools.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Learning Journey Map -->
      <div
        class="bg-[var(--surface)] border-l-4 border-[var(--accent)] p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg"
      >
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">
          &#x1f9ed; Learning Journey Map
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mb-4">
          I've been down this rabbit hole since 2005. The path isn't linear &mdash; you'll circle back, get distracted
          by shiny new tools, and occasionally wonder why Docker won't start. That's normal. Here's the progression I
          wish someone had laid out for me.
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-sm">
          <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem]">
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f331; Start Here</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
              Docker, basic monitoring, and one programming language. Don't try to learn everything at once.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem]">
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f680; Build Momentum</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
              Add orchestration, monitoring, and start breaking things intentionally. Security mindset begins here.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem]">
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f52c; Go Deep</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
              Specialize in what interests you. Red team, blue team, DevOps, or just really cool home automation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Books -->
      <h2 id="books" class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-12 mb-4">
        &#x1f4da; Books That Actually Taught Me Something
      </h2>

      <div
        class="bg-[var(--surface)] border-l-4 border-[var(--text-muted)] p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg"
      >
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">&#x1f4d6; My Reading Philosophy</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mb-4">
          I'm a hands-on learner, so books that combine theory with practical exercises work best for me. These aren't
          affiliate links &ndash; just books that made me better at what I do. I've listed them roughly in the order I'd
          recommend reading them, with personal notes about what makes each special.
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-sm">
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f4da; Start Here</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">Foundation books that build core knowledge</p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f52c; Go Deeper</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">Technical deep dives for specific skills</p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-3 rounded-[0.25rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <strong class="text-[var(--accent)]">&#x1f9e0; Perspective</strong>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
              Stories and context that change how you think
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Security Essentials Books -->
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-8 mb-4">Security Essentials</h3>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
        <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem]">
          <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">Technical Deep Dives</h5>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4da; <strong>START HERE:</strong>
                <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Web-Application-Hackers-Handbook-Exploiting/dp/1118026470"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">The Web Application Hacker's Handbook</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                <strong>Read:</strong> 2012, re-read: 2023 | <strong>Impact:</strong> Taught me to think like an attacker.
                Still reference Chapter 9 (attacking authentication) regularly.
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                <strong>Time investment:</strong> ~40 hours spread over 3 months | <strong>Value:</strong> Foundational. Everything
                else builds on this.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--accent)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d5; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Practical-Malware-Analysis-Hands-Dissecting/dp/1593272901"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Practical Malware Analysis</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                <strong>Read:</strong> 2014-2015, ~80 hours total | <strong>Setup time:</strong> 8 hours building isolated
                analysis environment
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                <strong>Learned:</strong> Reverse engineering, PE file structure, behavioral analysis | <strong
                  >Still use:</strong
                > IDA Free for quick binary analysis
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d7; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Network-Security-Through-Data-Analysis/dp/1491962844"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Network Security Through Data Analysis</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                Turn packet captures into intelligence. This book taught me to think like data, not just look at it.
                Great for building SIEM detection rules.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d9; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Rtfm-Red-Team-Field-Manual/dp/1494295504"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">RTFM: Red Team Field Manual</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                Cheat codes for pentesters. Keep this handy during engagements. Not for learning fundamentals, but great
                for quick reference when you're in the thick of it.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem]">
          <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">Mind-Expanding Reads</h5>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4da; <strong>START HERE:</strong>
                <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Cuckoos-Egg-Tracking-Computer-Espionage/dp/1416507787"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">The Cuckoo's Egg</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                The OG hacker hunt story. Written in 1989 but feels modern. Shows that good investigative techniques are
                timeless. Made me appreciate the detective work in security.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d5; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Sandworm-Cyberwar-Kremlins-Dangerous-Hackers/dp/0385544405"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Sandworm</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                Nation-state hacking that puts cybersecurity in a geopolitical context. Understanding state-level cyber
                warfare helps you think bigger than just technical vulnerabilities.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--accent)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d7; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Ghost-Wires-Adventures-Worlds-Wanted/dp/0316037729"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Ghost in the Wires</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                Kevin Mitnick's wild ride. Shows that social engineering often beats technical attacks. Changed how I
                think about human factors in security.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-3">
              <p>
                &#x1f4d9; <a
                  href="https://www.amazon.com/Cult-Dead-Cow-Original-Supergroup/dp/154176238X"
                  class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer">Cult of the Dead Cow</a>
              </p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                The hackers who shaped the internet. Great for understanding the culture and ethics that drive security
                research. Made me appreciate the history behind modern tools.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Homelab & DevOps Books -->
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-8 mb-4">Homelab &amp; DevOps</h3>

      <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem] my-6">
        <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">Level Up Your Lab</h5>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <ul class="text-[var(--text-muted)] space-y-2">
            <li>
              &#x1f527; <a
                href="https://www.amazon.com/Phoenix-Project-DevOps-Helping-Business/dp/1942788290"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">The Phoenix Project</a
              >
              <br /><span class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]"
                >DevOps explained through a story that hits too close to home</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              &#x2699;&#xfe0f; <a
                href="https://www.amazon.com/Site-Reliability-Engineering-Production-Systems/dp/149192912X"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Site Reliability Engineering</a
              >
              <br /><span class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]"
                >How Google does it (free online too!)</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <ul class="text-[var(--text-muted)] space-y-2">
            <li>
              &#x1f433; <a
                href="https://www.amazon.com/Docker-Deep-Dive-Poulton-Nigel/dp/1916585256"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Docker Deep Dive</a
              >
              <br /><span class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]"
                >Actually understand containers</span>
            </li>
            <li>
              &#x2638;&#xfe0f; <a
                href="https://www.amazon.com/Kubernetes-Book-Version-November-2018-ebook/dp/B072TS9ZQZ"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">The Kubernetes Book</a
              >
              <br /><span class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]">K8s without the pain</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Graveyard -->
      <h2 id="graveyard" class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-12 mb-4">
        &#x1f480; The Graveyard: Tools That Didn't Make the Cut
      </h2>

      <div
        class="bg-[var(--surface)] border-l-4 border-[var(--text)] p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg"
      >
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">&#x1faa6; Learn from My Mistakes</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mb-4">
          Not every tool is a winner. Here are some that looked promising but didn't survive contact with reality.
          Learning what doesn't work is just as valuable as finding what does.
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-4 rounded-[0.375rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <h4 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-2">OpenShift (for homelab)</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              <strong>Tried:</strong> Q2 2022, abandoned after 2 months<br />
              <strong>Cost:</strong> $0 but ~40 hours wasted<br />
              <strong>Why I tried it:</strong> Red Hat magic, enterprise features, impressive demos<br />
              <strong>Why it failed:</strong> Minimum 4 cores + 16GB RAM per node. Ate 64GB of my 256GB total RAM. K3s does
              90% for 10% of resources.<br />
              <strong>What I learned:</strong> Enterprise tools don't scale down. Use tools designed for your scale.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-4 rounded-[0.375rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <h4 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-2">Jenkins (for simple CI/CD)</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              <strong>Why I tried it:</strong> Industry standard, huge plugin ecosystem<br />
              <strong>Why it failed:</strong> Configuration nightmare. Spent more time maintaining Jenkins than using it.
              GitLab CI or Drone CI work better for small projects.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-4 rounded-[0.375rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <h4 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-2">Full ELK Stack (personal use)</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              <strong>Why I tried it:</strong> Industry standard logging<br />
              <strong>Why it failed:</strong> Java memory hog for homelab scale. Loki + Grafana gives 80% of the value with
              20% of the complexity.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div
            class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-4 rounded-[0.375rem] border border-[var(--border)]"
          >
            <h4 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-2">OSSEC (before Wazuh)</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              <strong>Why I tried it:</strong> Free SIEM solution<br />
              <strong>Why it failed:</strong> Configuration by editing XML files. In 2023. Wazuh is what OSSEC should have
              become.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="mt-4 p-3 bg-[var(--surface)] rounded-[0.25rem] border border-[var(--text-muted)]"
        >
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text)]">
            <strong>&#x1f4a1; The pattern:</strong> Complex enterprise tools often don't scale down well to homelab environments.
            Look for tools designed for simplicity first, then scale up if needed. See my <a href="/uses" class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline">/uses</a> page for the tools that did make the cut.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Fun Homelab Projects -->
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-12 mb-4">
        &#x1f3ae; Fun Homelab Projects
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] mb-6">
        Because learning should be fun, here are some projects that'll teach you tons:
      </p>

      <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem] my-6">
        <h4 class="text-xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-4">Weekend Warriors</h4>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[var(--accent)] pl-4">
            <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)]">&#x1f36f; Build a Honeypot Network</h5>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              Deploy <a
                href="https://github.com/telekom-security/tpotce"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">T-Pot</a
              > and watch the internet try to hack you. Grab popcorn.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-4">
            <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)]">&#x1f510; Red Team Lab</h5>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              Set up <a
                href="https://github.com/Orange-Cyberdefense/GOAD"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">GOAD</a
              > (Game of Active Directory) and practice your pentest skills.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-4">
            <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)]">&#x1f4e1; WiFi Pineapple DIY</h5>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              Build your own with a Raspberry Pi and <a
                href="https://github.com/wifiphisher/wifiphisher"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">Wifiphisher</a
              >. Test your network's security.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[var(--text)] pl-4">
            <h5 class="font-bold text-[var(--text)]">&#x1f3af; Malware Analysis Lab</h5>
            <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
              Set up <a
                href="https://remnux.org/"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">REMnux</a
              > and <a
                href="https://github.com/mandiant/flare-vm"
                class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">FLARE-VM</a
              > for safe malware analysis.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Learning Platforms -->
      <h2 id="learning" class="text-3xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-12 mb-4">
        &#x1f393; Learning Platforms Worth Your Time
      </h2>

      <div
        class="bg-[var(--surface)] border-l-4 border-[var(--accent)] p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg"
      >
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text)] mb-3">&#x1f3af; My Learning Strategy</h3>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)]">
          I learn best by doing, failing, and trying again. Start with free platforms to find what clicks for you, then
          invest money in areas where you want to go deeper.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Free Platforms -->
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-8 mb-4">
        Free Stuff That's Actually Good
      </h3>

      <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem] my-6">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          <div>
            <h5 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-3">Hands-On Labs</h5>
            <div class="space-y-3">
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f3af; <a
                    href="https://overthewire.org/wargames/"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">OverTheWire</a
                  > - Start with Bandit, thank me later
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                  <strong>Started:</strong> November 2010, still recommend |
                  <strong>Lessons:</strong> Linux basics, SSH, bash scripting, basic crypto |
                  <strong>Progression:</strong> Bandit &rarr; Leviathan &rarr; Natas &rarr; Krypton
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--accent)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f3f4; <a
                    href="https://picoctf.org/"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">PicoCTF</a
                  > - Beginner-friendly CTF
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                  Designed for high schoolers but perfect for adults learning fundamentals. Hint system prevents frustration.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f513; <a
                    href="https://portswigger.net/web-security"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">PortSwigger Academy</a
                  > - Free web security training
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-[var(--text-muted)] mt-1">
                  Made by the Burp Suite team. Interactive labs that teach real vulnerabilities.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h5 class="font-medium text-[var(--text)] mb-3">YouTube Channels</h5>
            <div class="space-y-3">
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f4fa; <a
                    href="https://www.youtube.com/@ippsec"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">IppSec</a
                  > - HTB walkthroughs that teach methodology, not just answers
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--accent)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f3ac; <a
                    href="https://www.youtube.com/@_JohnHammond"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">John Hammond</a
                  > - CTFs and malware analysis with clear explanations
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f3a5; <a
                    href="https://www.youtube.com/@NetworkChuck"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">NetworkChuck</a
                  > - Makes networking fun, great for homelab inspiration
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text-muted)] pl-3">
                <p>
                  &#x1f4f9; <a
                    href="https://www.youtube.com/@LiveOverflow"
                    class="text-[var(--accent)] hover:underline font-medium"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer">LiveOverflow</a
                  > - Deep technical dives into the "why" behind exploits
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Worth Paying For -->
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text)] mt-8 mb-4">Worth Paying For</h3>

      <div class="bg-[var(--surface)] p-6 rounded-[0.75rem] my-6">
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="border-l-2 border-[var(--text)] pl-4">
            <p>
              <a
                href="https://tryhackme.com/"
